HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1168
By Capley
A RESOLUTION to honor the memories of Preston W. Carroll and
Dorothy I. "Darbo" Carroll of Clifton.
WHEREAS, it is our pleasure to acknowledge the memory of those venerable sons and
daughters of Tennessee who were distinguished community leaders during their lifetimes; and
WHEREAS, two such noble citizens of the Volunteer State were Preston W. Carroll and
Dorothy I. "Darbo" Carroll of Clifton, whose legacies serve as shining examples of excellence in
their every endeavor; and
WHEREAS, Preston Carroll came to Wayne County in early 1952 to work on a
construction job in Waynesboro; by the end of the year, he was married to the love of his life,
Dorothy I. "Darbo" Cole, and the young couple would make Clifton their home; and
WHEREAS, for the first twelve years of their marriage, the Carrolls lived with Darbo's
parents, Rex and Roberta Cole, in downtown Clifton and began their family, having two sons
and one daughter, Preston Cole, Clyde, and Ann; and
WHEREAS, in 1961, as the expanding family needed a home of their own, Preston
Carroll traveled by boat up and down the Tennessee River to locate the perfect spot for a home
site, which became known as Sunset Bend and is now located at 734 W. Pillow Street; and
WHEREAS, the Carrolls' new home was built by James Cook, Sr., and took two years to
complete before they moved in May 1964; that next year, the family expanded again with the
birth of two more daughters, Dorothy "Jeanie" and Martha Jane "Janie"; and
WHEREAS, during his years of industry, Preston Carroll was a prominent businessman
in Clifton and employed many residents of Wayne County; he owned construction companies,
coal mines in Kentucky and West Virginia, a limestone mine and limestone kiln in East
Tennessee, and Mid-Tenn tractor company in Nashville; and
