WHEREAS, Mr. Carroll's office was located on the current site of Columbia State
Community College; he also owned real estate that is now the property of the State of
Tennessee, which is the site of several prisons; and
WHEREAS, an active part of his community, Mr. Carroll sponsored many of the athletic
teams and sports at Frank Hughes School, where his children participated over the years; he
was a dedicated member of First Presbyterian Church in Clifton, which he served as a Sunday
School superintendent, elder, and teacher of the men's Sunday School class; and
WHEREAS, after their last child went off to college, the Carrolls relocated to Nashville
near where their youngest daughters were attending school and spent the next nineteen years
in Nashville; and
WHEREAS, upon Darbo Carroll's passing in February 2006, Preston Carroll returned to
Sunset Bend and began a major renovation of the family home, which was completed in 2008,
with the work done by James and Tommy Cook, the sons of the original builder; and
WHEREAS, Preston Carroll would enjoy living at Sunset Bend on the banks of the
Tennessee River until his passing in November 2014; and
WHEREAS, Preston and Darbo Carroll were public-spirited citizens of the highest order
and most worthy of our approbation; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend the memories of Preston W. Carroll and Dorothy
I. "Darbo" Carroll for their manifold contributions to their family, their fellow citizens, and the
State of Tennessee.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
